SOLID principles
1. Single Responsibility Principle
    - A class should have only one reason to change.
    - Every class should do exactly one thing. If it handles more than one concern, split it up.
    - In Spring Boot Controller handles HTTP, Service handles business logic, Repository handles DB. That separation IS SRP in action.
    - ex :
        public class UserRepository {
          public void save(String name,
                           String email) {
            db.save(name, email);
          }
        }

        public class EmailService {
          public void sendWelcome(
                String name, String email) {
            emailClient.send(
              email, "Welcome " + name);
          }
        }

        public class UserLogger {
          public void logCreated(String name){
            logger.info(
              "User created: " + name);
          }
        }

    - Do not do this :
        public class UserService {

          public void createUser(String name,
                                 String email) {
            // 1. Save to DB
            db.save(name, email);

            // 2. Send welcome email
            emailClient.send(
              email,
              "Welcome " + name
            );

            // 3. Write to log
            logger.info(
              "User created: " + name
            );
          }
        }

    - simple thing we can apply to any class, we can check "what are the reasons this class might change?" If you can list more than one answer, it's an SRP violation.
    - A quick rule of thumb for each Spring Boot layer:
        . @RestController — only reads request, calls service, returns response. Nothing else.
        . @Service — only orchestrates or contains one specific piece of business logic
        . @Repository — only talks to the DB. No if-else, no formatting, no external calls
        . @Component — one focused utility (formatting, validation, encoding, etc.)

2. Open/Closed Principle
    - Open for extension, closed for modification.
    - Add new features by writing new code — never by editing existing, tested, working code. Use interfaces and polymorphism.
    - Ex :
        Good — add new type = new class only

        public interface PaymentGateway {
          void pay(double amount);
        }

        public class UpiPayment
               implements PaymentGateway {
          public void pay(double amount) {
            System.out.println(
              "Paid via UPI: " + amount);
          }
        }

        public class CardPayment
               implements PaymentGateway {
          public void pay(double amount) {
            System.out.println(
              "Paid via Card: " + amount);
          }
        }

        // Add PayPal? Just new class.
        // Zero changes to existing code.

    - Do not do this
        Bad — add new type = edit old code

        public class PaymentService {

          public void pay(String type,
                          double amount) {
            if (type.equals("UPI")) {
              System.out.println(
                "Paid via UPI: " + amount);
            } else if (type.equals("CARD")) {
              System.out.println(
                "Paid via Card: " + amount);
            }
            // Add PayPal?
            // You MUST edit this class!
          }
        }

3. Liskov Substitution Principle
   - Subclasses must be substitutable for their parent class without breaking the program.
   - If class B extends class A, you should be able to use B anywhere A is used — and nothing should break or surprise you.
   - Ex :
        Good — honest, independent classes
        public interface Shape {
          int area();
        }

        public class Rectangle
               implements Shape {
          private int width, height;

          public Rectangle(int w, int h) {
            this.width = w;
            this.height = h;
          }
          public int area() {
            return width * height;
          }
        }

        public class Square
               implements Shape {
          private int side;

          public Square(int side) {
            this.side = side;
          }
          public int area() {
            return side * side;
          }
        }
        // Both implement Shape.
        // No surprises. No overrides.

        - Do not do this
        Bad — subclass breaks parent's contract
        public class Rectangle {
          protected int width, height;

          public void setWidth(int w) {
            this.width = w;
          }
          public void setHeight(int h) {
            this.height = h;
          }
          public int area() {
            return width * height;
          }
        }

        public class Square extends Rectangle {
          // Breaks LSP! Square forces both sides equal — but caller doesn't know that.
          public void setWidth(int w) {
            this.width = w;
            this.height = w; // surprise!
          }
        }

4. Interface Segregation Principle
    - No class should be forced to implement methods it doesn't need.
    - Split fat interfaces into smaller, focused ones. A class should only implement what it actually uses — not carry dead weight.
    - Ex :
        Good — small focused interfaces
        public interface Workable {
          void work();
        }

        public interface Eatable {
          void eat();
        }

        public interface Sleepable {
          void sleep();
        }

        // Human implements all three
        public class Human implements
          Workable, Eatable, Sleepable {
          public void work()  { /*...*/ }
          public void eat()   { /*...*/ }
          public void sleep() { /*...*/ }
        }

        // Robot only implements what it needs
        public class Robot
               implements Workable {
          public void work() {
            System.out.println("Working...");
          }
        }

    - Do not do this
        Bad — fat interface forces junk methods
        public interface Worker {
          void work();
          void eat();
          void sleep();
        }

        // Robot doesn't eat or sleep!
        // But is FORCED to implement them.
        public class Robot implements Worker {
          public void work() {
            System.out.println("Working...");
          }
          public void eat() {
            // meaningless — robots don't eat
          }
          public void sleep() {
            // meaningless — robots don't sleep
          }
        }

5. Dependency Inversion Principle
    - High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules.
    - Both should depend on abstractions.
    - High-level module → business logic (what your app does)
    - Low-level module → implementation details (database, APIs, file system, etc.)
    - Depend on "what it does", not "how it does it"
    - DIP says:
        . Your business logic should NOT depend directly on concrete implementations.
        . Instead, both should depend on interfaces / abstractions.
    - Without DIP (Bad Design)
      Example: Order system
      class MySQLDatabase {
          void save(String data) {
              System.out.println("Saved to MySQL");
          }
      }

      class OrderService {
          private MySQLDatabase db = new MySQLDatabase();

          void placeOrder() {
              db.save("order data");
          }
      }

    // Problems:
    // OrderService is tightly coupled to MySQLDatabase
    // Switching to PostgreSQL? You must change OrderService
    // Hard to test (no mocking)

    - With DIP (Good Design)
    Step 1: Create abstraction
    interface Database {
        void save(String data);
    }

    Step 2: Low-level implements abstraction
    class MySQLDatabase implements Database {
        public void save(String data) {
            System.out.println("Saved to MySQL");
        }
    }

    Step 3: High-level depends on abstraction
    class OrderService {
        private Database db;

        OrderService(Database db) {
            this.db = db;
        }

        void placeOrder() {
            db.save("order data");
        }
    }

    Step 4: Inject dependency
    Database db = new MySQLDatabase();
    OrderService service = new OrderService(db);
    service.placeOrder();


